The Story
─────────

I am building a rule-based engine that lets you get coding tasks done with
far fewer tokens than usual.

Today's models are getting smarter. You don't need to spoonfeed them every
granular detail to get a task finished. But the token bill doesn't know that —
you're still paying for every character of every long identifier, every comment,
every repeated type name, even though the model would have understood a much
shorter representation just as well.

miniKen shifts that compute burden onto your local machine. Before a prompt
leaves your laptop, the engine compresses your source code into a dense symbolic
form. The model works on that. When the response comes back, the engine expands
it again. The model never sees the verbose originals; you never see the compact
symbols. Everything in between is cheaper.

You are offloading pre- and post-processing to idle local CPU, rather than
paying remote resources to shuffle tokens that carry no extra information.
For teams running many coding queries a day this is a meaningful cost difference.


The Pipeline
────────────

  Your Code
      │
      ▼
  [Compressor]  ──  two-pass tree-sitter parse
      │               Pass 1: walk AST, register every definition,
      │                       build compact-id map, strip comments
      │               Pass 2: re-emit source with all identifiers
      │                       replaced by their compact symbols
      │
      ▼
  Compressed Context  (typically 47 % fewer tokens, 65 % fewer chars)
      │
      ▼
  [ Model ]  ──  works entirely in compact-symbol space
      │
      ▼
  Compressed Response  (compact symbols + [FILE: name] sections)
      │
      ▼
  [Decompressor]  ──  reverse-maps every symbol back to its original,
      │                restores stripped comment blocks,
      │                expands {{symbol}} markers in textual replies
      ▼
  Patched Code  ──  your original identifiers, fully restored


Symbol Scheme
─────────────

  f   function / method              getUserBalance  →  f1
  C   class / struct                 CustomerOrder   →  C1
  v   variable / field / type        accountId       →  v3
  p   package / import               #include <map>  →  p2

Every symbol is scoped to a session and a project. Two projects processed in
the same session never share symbol counters, so files from different repos
can be compressed together without collision.


Architecture Highlights
───────────────────────

Language-agnostic core
  All compression and decompression logic is language-neutral. Language
  knowledge (which AST node types are definitions, which are identifiers,
  which are declarator wrappers) lives in a LanguageProfile struct. Adding
  support for a new language means writing one profile file — nothing else
  changes.

  Currently implemented: C++ (via tree-sitter-cpp).
  Planned: Python, Java, JavaScript (tree-sitter grammars exist for all).

Session isolation
  Every call creates a fresh SessionMapObject that holds all symbol maps and
  counters. No global state. Multiple concurrent sessions never interfere.

Two-pass compression (querySquasher)
  Pass 1 registers definitions with their correct type prefix (f/C/v/p),
  building the forward and reverse maps.
  Pass 2 replaces every identifier occurrence — not just definitions, but
  all call sites too — so the compressed output is self-consistent.

Round-trip fidelity (responseBuilder)
  The decompressor re-parses the compressed response with the same grammar,
  finds every compact symbol, and swaps it back. Comment blocks stripped
  during compression are re-attached before their definitions on the way out.


Project Layout
──────────────

  engine/
    orchestrator.h/.cpp        entry point: Orchestrator::run()
    parser/
      languageProfile.h        LanguageProfile struct (language-neutral)
      cppProfile.h/.cpp        C++ grammar + node-type knowledge
      querySquasher.h/.cpp     two-pass compressor
      responseBuilder.h/.cpp   decompressor
    compressor/
      commentOut.h/.cpp        strips and stores comment blocks
      compactBlock.h/.cpp      maps long names → compact symbols
    decompressor/
      relaxCommentOut.h/.cpp   restores comment blocks
      relaxCompactBlock.h/.cpp restores identifiers in source
      relaxTextual.h/.cpp      expands {{symbol}} in LLM text
    sessionStore/
      sessionMapObject.h/.cpp  in-memory symbol maps + counters
    static/
      prompt_format            system prompt sent to the model

  testbed/
    cli/miniken.cpp            command-line driver
    stages/
      cpp/                     C++ original / compressed / decompressed
      python/                  Python  ─┐
      java/                    Java    ─┤  stage files showing what
      javascript/              JS      ─┘  each pipeline stage looks like
    tests/                     92 unit + integration tests
    performance/benchmark.cpp  token-reduction benchmark


Real Numbers  (benchmark across 5 representative C++ samples)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  Average token reduction  :  47 %
  Average character reduction:  65 %

  A 164-token authentication module compresses to 99 tokens.
  A 141-token payment pipeline compresses to 64 tokens.


Integration Paths
─────────────────

CLI (works today)
  export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY="sk-ant-..."
  ./testbed_build/miniken "your question" src/foo.cpp src/bar.cpp

Claude Code — MCP server (recommended next step)
  Wrap the miniken binary in a ~100-line Python MCP server.
  Register one tool: miniken_query(question, files[]).
  Claude Code calls it automatically when working on C++ files.

VSCode extension
  A sidebar that lets you pick files, type a query, and see the
  decompressed response alongside compression statistics.
